<TITLE> Stocks continue to trade down </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 2 (bdnews24.com)The Dhaka stock exchange continued to trade down Wednesday from the previous day driven by banks and insurance sector shares. The market saw decreased activity both from institutional and retail investors. The gloomy outlook prevailing in the market is mainly due to reduced participation of institutional investors as they are now busy closing their accounts, said a top official of a brokerage house. AIMS of Bangladesh CEO Yaweer Sayeed termed the market slowdown a regular phenomenon at this time of the year. "The last week of a year and the first week of new year usually see decreased transactions as the institutional investors are busy taking care of their accounts." He also pointed out the possibility of market corrections as a reason for the decreased participation of retail investors. "Retail investors could also be holding their cash as they are waiting for the state-run oil companies, Jamuna and Meghna, to list on the market," Sayeed added. The benchmark DGEN or general index shed 49.55 points or 1.64 percent to end at 2959.36. The DSI or all share price index closed at 2491.72, down 37.93 points or 1.49 percent. The DSE-20 blue chip index also fell 59.96 points or 2.4 percent to 2435.69. Turnover at the country's prime bourse stood at Tk 1.16 billion from trading of 5,971,480 shares. Losers outnumbered gainers 146 to 76 and some 10 issues held steady. AB Bank fell 0.37 percent to close at Tk 2631.75. Market major Square Pharma closed at Tk 3593.75, down 3.83 percent. IFIC Bank edged up 2.15 percent, on the report of the regulator easing a rule to facilitate the government in offloading its stakes in the bank. It closed at Tk 2449.25. BRAC Bank continued to decline on profit taking, slumping 0.88 percent to end at Tk 1562.25. State owned Power Grid Company of Bangladesh fell 4.24 percent to Tk 653.50. Meanwhile, the stock market watchdog has disapproved the rights share offer of Summit Power as one of the directors of the company was found to be a loan defaulter. Among other active scripsNBL, Islami Bank Perpetual Bond, Islami Bank and UCBL fell. Fareast Life Insurance gained. BD Zipper Industries, Meghna Pet Industries, Sajib Knitwear, Bengal Biscuits and Paper Processing were among the major gainers. Aziz Pipes, Samata Leather, Bangladesh Thai Aluminum, Social Investment Bank and Gachihata Aquaculture led the losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended lower with all sectors declining except insurance and food sector shares. The CSCX or selective categories index closed at 4813.77, down 86.79 points or 1.77 percent. The CASPI or all share price index fell 123.76 points or 1.62 percent to 7502.57, while the bourse's blue chip index shed 139.92 points or 2.01 percent to close at 6800.73. Turnover on the port city's bourse stood at Tk 192.327 million from trading of 1,714,730 shares. Of the issues traded 33 advanced, 86 declined and 6 remained unchanged. bdne
